# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alphafold-prediction
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] AlphaFold 1 (2018) placed first in the overall rankings of the 13th Critical Assessment of Structure Prediction (CASP) in December 2018.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] It was particularly successful at predicting the most accurate structures for targets rated as most difficult by the competition organizers, where no existing template structures were available from proteins with partially similar sequences.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] AlphaFold 2 (2020) repeated this placement in the CASP14 competition in November 2020.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] It achieved a level of accuracy much higher than any other entry.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] It scored above 90 on CASP's global distance test (GDT) for approximately two-thirds of the proteins, a test measuring the similarity between a computationally predicted structure and the experimentally determined structure, where 100 represents a complete match.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] The inclusion of metagenomic data has improved the quality of the prediction of multiple sequence alignments.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] One of the biggest sources of the training data was the custom-built Big Fantastic Database of 65,983,866 protein families, represented as multiple sequence alignments and Hidden Markov models, covering 2,204,359,010 protein sequences from reference databases, metagenomes, and metatranscriptomes.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] AlphaFold 2's results at CASP14 were described as "astounding" and "transformational".
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] However, some researchers noted that the accuracy was insufficient for a third of its predictions, and that it did not reveal the underlying mechanism or rules of protein folding for the protein folding problem, which remains unsolved.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] Despite this, the technical achievement was widely recognized.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] On 15 July 2021, the AlphaFold 2 paper was published in *Nature* as an advance access publication alongside open source software and a searchable database of species proteomes.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] As of November 2025, the paper had been cited nearly 43,000 times.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] AlphaFold 3 was announced on 8 May 2024.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] It can predict the structure of complexes created by proteins with DNA, RNA, various ligands, and ions.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] The new prediction method shows a minimum 50% improvement in accuracy for protein interactions with other molecules compared to existing methods.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] Proteins consist of chains of amino acids which spontaneously fold to form the three dimensional (3-D) structures of the proteins.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] The 3-D structure is necessary to understanding the biological function of the protein.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] Protein structures can be determined experimentally through techniques such as X-ray crystallography, cryo-electron microscopy and nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR), which are all expensive and time-consuming.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] Such efforts, using the experimental methods, have identified the structures of about 170,000 proteins over the last 60 years, while there are over 200 million known proteins across all life forms.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] Over the years, researchers have applied numerous computational methods to predict the 3D structures of proteins from their amino acid sequences, accuracy of such methods in best possible scenario is close to experimental techniques (NMR) by the use of homology modeling based on molecular evolution.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] CASP, which was launched in 1994 to challenge the scientific community to produce their best protein structure predictions, found that GDT scores of only about 40 out of 100 can be achieved for the most difficult proteins by 2016.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] AlphaFold started competing in the 2018 CASP using an artificial intelligence (AI) deep learning technique.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] DeepMind is known to have trained the program on over 170,000 protein structures from the Protein Data Bank, a public repository of protein sequences and structures.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] The program uses a form of attention network, a deep learning technique that focuses on having the AI identify parts of a larger problem, then piece it together to obtain the overall solution.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] The overall training was conducted on processing power between 100 and 200 GPUs.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] The 2020 version of the program (**AlphaFold 2**, 2020) is significantly different from the original version that won CASP 13 in 2018, according to the team at DeepMind.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] AlphaFold 1 used a number of separately trained modules to produce a guide potential, which was then combined with a physics-based energy potential.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] AlphaFold 2 replaced this with a system of interconnected sub-networks, forming a single, differentiable, end-to-end model based on pattern recognition.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] This model was trained in an integrated manner.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] After the neural network's prediction converges, a final refinement step applies local physical constraints using energy minimization based on the AMBER force field.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] This step only slightly adjusts the predicted structure.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] Internally these refinement transformations contain layers that have the effect of bringing relevant data together and filtering out irrelevant data (the "attention mechanism") for these relationships, in a context-dependent way, learned from training data.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] The output of these iterations then informs the final structure prediction module, which also uses transformers, and is itself then iterated.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] In an example presented by DeepMind, the structure prediction module achieved a correct topology for the target protein on its first iteration, scored as having a GDT_TS of 78, but with a large number (90%) of stereochemical violations – i.e. unphysical bond angles or lengths.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] With subsequent iterations the number of stereochemical violations fell.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] By the third iteration the GDT_TS of the prediction was approaching 90, and by the eighth iteration the number of stereochemical violations was approaching zero.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] The training data was originally restricted to single peptide chains.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] However, the October 2021 update, named AlphaFold-Multimer, included protein complexes in its training data.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] DeepMind stated this update succeeded about 70% of the time at accurately predicting protein-protein interactions.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] Announced on 8 May 2024, **AlphaFold 3** was co-developed by Google DeepMind and Isomorphic Labs, both subsidiaries of Alphabet.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] AlphaFold 3 is not limited to proteins, as it can also predict the structures of protein complexes with DNA, RNA, post-translational modifications and selected ligands and ions.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] AlphaFold 3 introduces the "Pairformer," a deep learning architecture inspired by the transformer, which is considered similar to, but simpler than, the Evoformer used in AlphaFold 2.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] The Pairformer module's initial predictions are refined by a diffusion model.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] This model begins with a cloud of atoms and iteratively refines their positions, guided by the Pairformer's output, to generate a 3D representation of the molecular structure.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] The AlphaFold server was created to provide free access to AlphaFold 3 for non-commercial research.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] As of November 2025, the AlphaFold 3 research paper has been directly cited more than 9,000 times.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] In December 2018, DeepMind's AlphaFold placed first in the overall rankings of the 13th Critical Assessment of Techniques for Protein Structure Prediction (CASP).
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] The program was particularly successfully predicting the most accurate structure for targets rated as the most difficult by the competition organisers, where no existing template structures were available from proteins with a partially similar sequence.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] AlphaFold gave the best prediction for 25 out of 43 protein targets in this class, achieving a median score of 58.9 on the CASP's global distance test (GDT) score, ahead of 52.5 and 52.4 by the two next best-placed teams, who were also using deep learning to estimate contact distances.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] Overall, across all targets, AlphaFold 1 achieved a GDT score of 68.5.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] In January 2020, implementations and illustrative code of AlphaFold 1 was released open-source on GitHub. but, as stated in the "Read Me" file on that website: "This code can't be used to predict structure of an arbitrary protein sequence.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] It can be used to predict structure only on the CASP13 dataset (links below).
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] The feature generation code is tightly coupled to our internal infrastructure as well as external tools, hence we are unable to open-source it." Therefore, in essence, the code deposited is not suitable for general use but only for the CASP13 proteins.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] The company has not announced plans to make their code publicly available as of 5 March 2021.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] In November 2020, DeepMind's new version, AlphaFold 2, won CASP14.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] Overall, AlphaFold 2 made the best prediction for 88 out of the 97 targets.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] In 2018 AlphaFold 1 had only reached this level of accuracy in two of all of its predictions.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] 88% of predictions in the 2020 competition had a GDT_TS score of more than 80.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] On the group of targets classed as the most difficult, AlphaFold 2 achieved a median score of 87.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] 76% of predictions achieved better than 3 Å, and 46% had a C-alpha atom RMS accuracy better than 2 Å, with a median RMS deviation in its predictions of 2.1 Å for a set of overlapped CA atoms.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] AlphaFold 2 also achieved an accuracy in modelling surface side chains described as "really really extraordinary".
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] To further validate AlphaFold 2, the conference organizers approached four leading experimental groups working on structures they found particularly challenging and had been unable to determine.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] In all four cases the three-dimensional models produced by AlphaFold 2 were sufficiently accurate to determine structures of these proteins by molecular replacement.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] These included target T1100 (Af1503), a small membrane protein studied by experimentalists for ten years.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] Of the three structures that AlphaFold 2 had the least success in predicting, one was an unusual multidomain complex consisting of 52 identical copies of the same domain.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] For all targets with a single domain, excluding only one very large protein and the two structures determined by NMR, AlphaFold 2 achieved a GDT_TS score of over 80.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] In 2022, DeepMind did not enter CASP15, but most of the entrants used AlphaFold or tools incorporating AlphaFold.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] AlphaFold 2 scoring more than 90 in CASP's global distance test (GDT) is a great achievement in computational biology.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] Nobel Prize winner and structural biologist Venki Ramakrishnan called the result "a stunning advance on the protein folding problem", adding that "It has occurred decades before many people in the field would have predicted.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] AlphaFold 2's success received wide media attention.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] News pieces appeared in the science press, such as *Nature*, *Science*, *MIT Technology Review*, and *New Scientist*, and the story was covered by national newspapers.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] A frequent theme was the ability to predict protein structures based on the constituent amino acid sequence, expected to have benefits in the life sciences—accelerating drug discovery and enabling better understanding of diseases.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] Some have noted that even a perfect answer to the protein *prediction* problem still leaves questions about the protein *folding* problem (and thus protein dynamics)—understanding in detail how the folding process actually occurs in nature (and how sometimes they can also misfold).
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] In 2023, Demis Hassabis and John Jumper won the Breakthrough Prize in Life Sciences as well as the Albert Lasker Award for Basic Medical Research for their management of the AlphaFold project.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] Hassabis and Jumper proceeded to win the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 2024 for their work on "protein structure prediction" with David Baker of the University of Washington.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] Open access to source code of several AlphaFold versions (excluding AlphaFold 3) has been provided by DeepMind in 2022 after requests from the scientific community.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] The source code and weights of AlphaFold 3 were made available for non-commercial use to the scientific community upon request in November 2024.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] It became publicly available in February 2025, still retaining the non-commercial restriction.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] A number of AlphaFold clones have also been published, mostly with permissive license terms.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] Clones for AlphaFold3 include ByteDance's Protenix (Apache 2.0 License), AlQuraishi Laboratory's OpenFold-3 (MIT license), and Boltz-1/2 (MIT license).
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] There are also clones for older versions, though they became less relevant with the open-source release of AlphaFold 1 and 2 source codes.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] Still relevant are models, both open- and closed-source, that include modifications to the AlphaFold architecture.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] For AlphaFold 2, a notable example is ESMFold from Meta, which replaces the multiple sequence alignment with the latent space of a protein language model.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] Open-source tools that complement AlphaFold have also been made.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] One well-cited example is ColabFold, which uses MMseqs2 instead of HHblits to speed up the sequence search, allowing the AlphaFold pipelines to run quickly on Google Colab.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] The **AlphaFold Protein Structure Database** (AFDB), a joint project between AlphaFold and EMBL-EBI, was launched on July 22, 2021.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] At launch, the database contained AlphaFold 1-predicted models for nearly the complete UniProt proteome of humans and 20 model organisms, totaling over 365,000 proteins.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] The database does not include proteins with fewer than 16 or more than 2700 amino acid residues, but for humans they are available in the whole batch file.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] AlphaFold's initial goal (as of early 2022) was to expand the database to cover most of the UniRef90 set, which contains over 100 million proteins.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] As of May 15, 2022, the database contained 992,316 predictions.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] In July 2021, UniProt-KB and InterPro has been updated to show AlphaFold predictions when available.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] On July 28, 2022, the team uploaded to the database the structures of around 200 million proteins from 1 million species, covering nearly every known protein on the planet.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] The number as of 2024 is 214 million, with 26 million being duplicates (exact sequence matches) of another protein in the database.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] The predicted structures can differ significantly between duplicates.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] As of 2025, the AFDB uses AlphaFold 2 for its predictions.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] All structures produced remain monomeric, but multimeric structures produced by other databases are linked on the page through the 3D-Beacons API.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] Foldseek, which provides fast and accurate structure searches, is also integrated.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] Information from AlphaMissense (a tool that uses AlphaFold to predict the outcome of missense mutations) is also integrated.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] AlphaFill adds cofactors to AlphaFold models where appropriate.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] This is achieved by searching the Protein Data Bank for similar structures and transplanting cofactors to analogous positions.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] TmAlphaFold docks AlphaFold models to biological membranes, similar to what OPM does for PDB structures.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] AFTM uses AlphaFold models to identify transmembrane regions in human proteins, similar to what PDBTM does for PDB structures.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] ChannelsDB 2.0 uses PDB or AlphaFill models to calculate the pathway a molecule may take to reach an enzyme's active site or to reach another side of a transmembrane pore.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] The AFDB is not updated with UniProt sequences changes.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] AlphaSync keeps the AFDB in sync with UniProt entry changes, generating updated structures, residue-level features and contacts.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] It tries to use an AFDB entry for the exact updated sequence when available and run AlphaFold 2 independently otherwise.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] It fills in AFDB's blank for large (> 2,700 aa) proteins and proteins with special FASTA characters such as B, Z, U or X.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] The Encyclopedia of Domains (TED) applies the domain-recognition method from CATH database to 188 million unique structures from the AFDB, identifying nearly 365 million domains, which is 100 million more than what sequence-based methods could identify.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] The Evolutionary Classification of Protein Domains database (ECOD) assigns ECOD classifications to all SwissProt proteins in AFDB.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] isoform.io is a database of AlphaFold2-generated structures of proposed splice isoforms in the human genome.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] It includes information from 237,275 human transcripts.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] It has been used to detect errors in the mRNA predictions for a handful of genes.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] AlphaFold has shown certain limitations.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] AlphaFold has been used to predict structures of proteins of SARS-CoV-2, the causative agent of COVID-19.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] The structures of these proteins were pending experimental detection in early 2020.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] Results were reviewed by scientists at the Francis Crick Institute in the United Kingdom before being released to the broader research community.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] The team also confirmed accurate prediction against the experimentally determined SARS-CoV-2 spike protein that was shared in the Protein Data Bank, an international open-access database, before releasing the computationally determined structures of the under-studied protein molecules.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] The team acknowledged that although these protein structures might not be the subject of ongoing therapeutical research efforts, they will add to the community's understanding of the SARS-CoV-2 virus.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] Specifically, AlphaFold 2's prediction of the structure of the *ORF3a* protein was very similar to the structure determined by researchers at University of California, Berkeley using cryo-electron microscopy.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] This specific protein is believed to assist the virus in breaking out of the host cell once it replicates.
[src:alphafold-prediction/alphafold] This protein is also believed to play a role in triggering the inflammatory response to the infection.
[src:alphafold-prediction/casp] Targets for structure prediction are either structures soon-to-be solved by X-ray crystallography or NMR spectroscopy, or structures that have just been solved (mainly by one of the structural genomics centers) and are kept on hold by the Protein Data Bank.
[src:alphafold-prediction/casp] If the given sequence is found to be related by common descent to a protein sequence of known structure (called a template), comparative protein modeling may be used to predict the tertiary structure.
[src:alphafold-prediction/casp] Templates can be found using sequence alignment methods (e.g.
[src:alphafold-prediction/casp] BLAST or HHsearch) or protein threading methods, which are better in finding distantly related templates.
[src:alphafold-prediction/casp] Otherwise, *de novo* protein structure prediction must be applied (e.g.
[src:alphafold-prediction/casp] Rosetta), which is much less reliable but can sometimes yield models with the correct fold (usually, for proteins less than 100-150 amino acids).
[src:alphafold-prediction/casp] Truly new folds are becoming quite rare among the targets, making that category smaller than desirable.
[src:alphafold-prediction/casp] The primary method of evaluation is a comparison of the predicted model α-carbon positions with those in the target structure.
[src:alphafold-prediction/casp] Free modeling (template-free, or *de novo*) is also evaluated visually by the assessors, since the numerical scores do not work as well for finding loose resemblances in the most difficult cases.
[src:alphafold-prediction/casp] High-accuracy template-based predictions were evaluated in CASP7 by whether they worked for molecular-replacement phasing of the target crystal structure with successes followed up later, and by full-model (not just α-carbon) model quality and full-model match to the target in CASP8.
[src:alphafold-prediction/casp] Starting with CASP7, categories have been redefined to reflect developments in methods.
[src:alphafold-prediction/casp] The 'Template based modeling' category includes all former comparative modeling, homologous fold based models and some analogous fold based models.
[src:alphafold-prediction/casp] The 'template free modeling (FM)' category includes models of proteins with previously unseen folds and hard analogous fold based models.
[src:alphafold-prediction/casp] Due to limited numbers of template free targets (they are quite rare), in 2011 so called CASP ROLL was introduced.
[src:alphafold-prediction/casp] This continuous (rolling) CASP experiment aims at more rigorous evaluation of template free prediction methods through assessment of a larger number of targets outside of the regular CASP prediction season.
[src:alphafold-prediction/casp] Unlike LiveBench and EVA, this experiment is in the blind-prediction spirit of CASP, i.e. all the predictions are made on yet unknown structures.
[src:alphafold-prediction/casp] The CASP results are published in special supplement issues of the scientific journal *Proteins*, all of which are accessible through the CASP website.
[src:alphafold-prediction/casp] A lead article in each of these supplements describes specifics of the experiment while a closing article evaluates progress in the field.
[src:alphafold-prediction/casp] In December 2018, CASP13 made headlines when it was won by AlphaFold, an artificial intelligence program created by DeepMind.
[src:alphafold-prediction/casp] In November 2020, an improved version 2 of AlphaFold won CASP14.
[src:alphafold-prediction/casp] According to one of CASP co-founders John Moult, AlphaFold scored around 90 on a 100-point scale of prediction accuracy for moderately difficult protein targets.
[src:alphafold-prediction/casp] AlphaFold was made open source in 2021, and in CASP15 in 2022, while DeepMind did not enter, virtually all of the high-ranking teams used AlphaFold or modifications of AlphaFold.
[src:alphafold-prediction/casp] Until 2025, funding for the competition was provided by a grant from the National Institutes of Health.
[src:alphafold-prediction/casp] However, the NIH did not renew funding for the program in 2025, due to budget cuts made by the Trump administration.
[src:alphafold-prediction/casp] The competition was on the verge of closing down before Google DeepMind stepped in to provide interim funding.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] Evolutionarily related proteins have similar sequences and naturally occurring homologous proteins have similar protein structure.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] It has been shown that three-dimensional protein structure is evolutionarily more conserved than would be expected on the basis of sequence conservation alone.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] The sequence alignment and template structure are then used to produce a structural model of the target.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] Because protein structures are more conserved than DNA sequences, and detectable levels of sequence similarity usually imply significant structural similarity.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] The quality of the homology model is dependent on the quality of the sequence alignment and template structure.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] Model quality declines with decreasing sequence identity; a typical model has ~1–2 Å root mean square deviation between the matched Cα atoms at 70% sequence identity but only 2–4 Å agreement at 25% sequence identity.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] However, the errors are significantly higher in the loop regions, where the amino acid sequences of the target and template proteins may be completely different.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] Regions of the model that were constructed without a template, usually by loop modeling, are generally much less accurate than the rest of the model.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] Errors in side chain packing and position also increase with decreasing identity, and variations in these packing configurations have been suggested as a major reason for poor model quality at low identity.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] Nevertheless, homology models can be useful in reaching *qualitative* conclusions about the biochemistry of the query sequence, especially in formulating hypotheses about why certain residues are conserved, which may in turn lead to experiments to test those hypotheses.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] For example, the spatial arrangement of conserved residues may suggest whether a particular residue is conserved to stabilize the folding, to participate in binding some small molecule, or to foster association with another protein or nucleic acid.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] Homology modeling can produce high-quality structural models when the target and template are closely related, which has inspired the formation of a structural genomics consortium dedicated to the production of representative experimental structures for all classes of protein folds.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] The chief inaccuracies in homology modeling, which worsen with lower sequence identity, derive from errors in the initial sequence alignment and from improper template selection.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] Like other methods of structure prediction, current practice in homology modeling is assessed in a biennial large-scale experiment known as the Critical Assessment of Techniques for Protein Structure Prediction, or Critical Assessment of Structure Prediction (CASP).
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] The method of homology modeling is based on the observation that protein tertiary structure is better conserved than amino acid sequence.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] Thus, even proteins that have diverged appreciably in sequence but still share detectable similarity will also share common structural properties, particularly the overall fold.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] There are exceptions to the general rule that proteins sharing significant sequence identity will share a fold.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] For example, a judiciously chosen set of mutations of less than 50% of a protein can cause the protein to adopt a completely different fold.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] However, such a massive structural rearrangement is unlikely to occur in evolution, especially since the protein is usually under the constraint that it must fold properly and carry out its function in the cell.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] For comparison, the function of a protein is conserved much *less* than the protein sequence, since relatively few changes in amino-acid sequence are required to take on a related function.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] The homology modeling procedure can be broken down into four sequential steps: template selection, target-template alignment, model construction, and model assessment.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] The first two steps are often essentially performed together, as the most common methods of identifying templates rely on the production of sequence alignments; however, these alignments may not be of sufficient quality because database search techniques prioritize speed over alignment quality.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] These processes can be performed iteratively to improve the quality of the final model, although quality assessments that are not dependent on the true target structure are still under development.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] The critical first step in homology modeling is the identification of the best template structure, if indeed any are available.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] The simplest method of template identification relies on serial pairwise sequence alignments aided by database search techniques such as FASTA and BLAST.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] More sensitive methods based on multiple sequence alignment – of which PSI-BLAST is the most common example – iteratively update their position-specific scoring matrix to successively identify more distantly related homologs.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] This family of methods has been shown to produce a larger number of potential templates and to identify better templates for sequences that have only distant relationships to any solved structure.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] Protein threading, also known as fold recognition or 3D-1D alignment, can also be used as a search technique for identifying templates to be used in traditional homology modeling methods.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] Recent CASP experiments indicate that some protein threading methods such as RaptorX are more sensitive than purely sequence(profile)-based methods when only distantly-related templates are available for the proteins under prediction.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] When performing a BLAST search, a reliable first approach is to identify hits with a sufficiently low *E*-value, which are considered sufficiently close in evolution to make a reliable homology model.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] Other factors may tip the balance in marginal cases; for example, the template may have a function similar to that of the query sequence, or it may belong to a homologous operon.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] However, a template with a poor *E*-value should generally not be chosen, even if it is the only one available, since it may well have a wrong structure, leading to the production of a misguided model.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] A better approach is to submit the primary sequence to fold-recognition servers or, better still, consensus meta-servers which improve upon individual fold-recognition servers by identifying similarities (consensus) among independent predictions.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] Often several candidate template structures are identified by these approaches.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] Although some methods can generate hybrid models with better accuracy from multiple templates, most methods rely on a single template.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] Therefore, choosing the best template from among the candidates is a key step, and can affect the final accuracy of the structure significantly.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] This choice is guided by several factors, such as the similarity of the query and template sequences, of their functions, and of the predicted query and observed template secondary structures.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] Perhaps most importantly, the *coverage* of the aligned regions: the fraction of the query sequence structure that can be predicted from the template, and the plausibility of the resulting model.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] Thus, sometimes several homology models are produced for a single query sequence, with the most likely candidate chosen only in the final step.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] It is possible to use the sequence alignment generated by the database search technique as the basis for the subsequent model production; however, more sophisticated approaches have also been explored.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] One proposal generates an ensemble of stochastically defined pairwise alignments between the target sequence and a single identified template as a means of exploring "alignment space" in regions of sequence with low local similarity.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] Given a template and an alignment, the information contained therein must be used to generate a three-dimensional structural model of the target, represented as a set of Cartesian coordinates for each atom in the protein.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] Three major classes of model generation methods have been proposed.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] The original method of homology modeling relied on the assembly of a complete model from conserved structural fragments identified in closely related solved structures.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] For example, a modeling study of serine proteases in mammals identified a sharp distinction between "core" structural regions conserved in all experimental structures in the class, and variable regions typically located in the loops where the majority of the sequence differences were localized.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] Thus unsolved proteins could be modeled by first constructing the conserved core and then substituting variable regions from other proteins in the set of solved structures.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] Current implementations of this method differ mainly in the way they deal with regions that are not conserved or that lack a template.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] The variable regions are often constructed with the help of a protein fragment library.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] The segment-matching method divides the target into a series of short segments, each of which is matched to its own template fitted from the Protein Data Bank.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] Thus, sequence alignment is done over segments rather than over the entire protein.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] Selection of the template for each segment is based on sequence similarity, comparisons of alpha carbon coordinates, and predicted steric conflicts arising from the van der Waals radii of the divergent atoms between target and template.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] The most common current homology modeling method takes its inspiration from calculations required to construct a three-dimensional structure from data generated by NMR spectroscopy.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] One or more target-template alignments are used to construct a set of geometrical criteria that are then converted to probability density functions for each restraint.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] Restraints applied to the main protein internal coordinates – protein backbone distances and dihedral angles – serve as the basis for a global optimization procedure that originally used conjugate gradient energy minimization to iteratively refine the positions of all heavy atoms in the protein.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] This method had been dramatically expanded to apply specifically to loop modeling, which can be extremely difficult due to the high flexibility of loops in proteins in aqueous solution.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] A more recent expansion applies the spatial-restraint model to electron density maps derived from cryoelectron microscopy studies, which provide low-resolution information that is not usually itself sufficient to generate atomic-resolution structural models.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] To address the problem of inaccuracies in initial target-template sequence alignment, an iterative procedure has also been introduced to refine the alignment on the basis of the initial structural fit.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] The most commonly used software in spatial restraint-based modeling is MODELLER and a database called ModBase has been established for reliable models generated with it.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] Regions of the target sequence that are not aligned to a template are modeled by loop modeling; they are the most susceptible to major modeling errors and occur with higher frequency when the target and template have low sequence identity.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] The coordinates of unmatched sections determined by loop modeling programs are generally much less accurate than those obtained from simply copying the coordinates of a known structure, particularly if the loop is longer than 10 residues.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] The first two sidechain dihedral angles (χ1 and χ2) can usually be estimated within 30° for an accurate backbone structure; however, the later dihedral angles found in longer side chains such as lysine and arginine are notoriously difficult to predict.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] Moreover, small errors in χ1 (and, to a lesser extent, in χ2) can cause relatively large errors in the positions of the atoms at the terminus of side chain; such atoms often have a functional importance, particularly when located near the active site.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] A large number of methods have been developed for selecting a native-like structure from a set of models.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] Scoring functions have been based on both molecular mechanics energy functions (Lazaridis and Karplus 1999; Petrey and Honig 2000; Feig and Brooks 2002; Felts et al.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] 2002; Lee and Duan 2004), statistical potentials (Sippl 1995; Melo and Feytmans 1998; Samudrala and Moult 1998; Rojnuckarin and Subramaniam 1999; Lu and Skolnick 2001; Wallqvist et al.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] 2002; Zhou and Zhou 2002), residue environments (Luthy et al.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] 2005), local side-chain and backbone interactions (Fang and Shortle 2005), orientation-dependent properties (Buchete et al.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] 2004a,b; Hamelryck 2005), packing estimates (Berglund et al.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] 2004), solvation energy (Petrey and Honig 2000; McConkey et al.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] 2003; Wallner and Elofsson 2003; Berglund et al.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] 2004), hydrogen bonding (Kortemme et al.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] 2003), and geometric properties (Colovos and Yeates 1993; Kleywegt 2000; Lovell et al.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] A number of methods combine different potentials into a global score, usually using a linear combination of terms (Kortemme et al.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] 2003; Tosatto 2005), or with the help of machine learning techniques, such as neural networks (Wallner and Elofsson 2003) and support vector machines (SVM) (Eramian et al.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] Comparisons of different global model quality assessment programs can be found in recent papers by Pettitt et al.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] Less work has been reported on the local quality assessment of models.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] Local scores are important in the context of modeling because they can give an estimate of the reliability of different regions of a predicted structure.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] This information can be used in turn to determine which regions should be refined, which should be considered for modeling by multiple templates, and which should be predicted ab initio.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] One of the most widely used local scoring methods is Verify3D (Luthy et al.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] 1997), which combines secondary structure, solvent accessibility, and polarity of residue environments.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] ProsaII (Sippl 1993), which is based on a combination of a pairwise statistical potential and a solvation term, is also applied extensively in model evaluation.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] Melo and Feytmans (1998) use an atomic pairwise potential and a surface-based solvation potential (both knowledge-based) to evaluate protein structures.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] Apart from the energy strain method, which is a semiempirical approach based on the ECEPP3 force field (Nemethy et al.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] 1992), all of the local methods listed above are based on statistical potentials.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] A conceptually distinct approach is the ProQres method, which was very recently introduced by Wallner and Elofsson (2006).
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] ProQres is based on a neural network that combines structural features to distinguish correct from incorrect regions.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] ProQres was shown to outperform earlier methodologies based on statistical approaches (Verify3D, ProsaII, and Errat).
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] The data presented in Wallner and Elofsson's study suggests that their machine-learning approach based on structural features is indeed superior to statistics-based methods.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] However, the knowledge-based methods examined in their work, Verify3D (Luthy et al.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] 1997), Prosa (Sippl 1993), and Errat (Colovos and Yeates 1993), are not based on newer statistical potentials.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] Several large-scale benchmarking efforts have been made to assess the relative quality of various current homology modeling methods.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] Its partner Critical Assessment of Fully Automated Structure Prediction (CAFASP) has run in parallel with CASP but evaluates only models produced via fully automated servers.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] Continuously running experiments that do not have prediction 'seasons' focus mainly on benchmarking publicly available webservers.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] LiveBench and EVA run continuously to assess participating servers' performance in prediction of imminently released structures from the PDB.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] CASP and CAFASP serve mainly as evaluations of the state of the art in modeling, while the continuous assessments seek to evaluate the model quality that would be obtained by a non-expert user employing publicly available tools.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] The accuracy of the structures generated by homology modeling is highly dependent on the sequence identity between target and template.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] Above 50% sequence identity, models tend to be reliable, with only minor errors in side chain packing and rotameric state, and an overall RMSD between the modeled and the experimental structure falling around 1 Å.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] This error is comparable to the typical resolution of a structure solved by NMR.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] In the 30–50% identity range, errors can be more severe and are often located in loops.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] Below 30% identity, serious errors occur, sometimes resulting in the basic fold being mis-predicted.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] This low-identity region is often referred to as the "twilight zone" within which homology modeling is extremely difficult, and to which it is possibly less suited than fold recognition methods.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] At high sequence identities, the primary source of error in homology modeling derives from the choice of the template or templates on which the model is based, while lower identities exhibit serious errors in sequence alignment that inhibit the production of high-quality models.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] Attempts have been made to improve the accuracy of homology models built with existing methods by subjecting them to molecular dynamics simulation in an effort to improve their RMSD to the experimental structure.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] However, current force field parameterizations may not be sufficiently accurate for this task, since homology models used as starting structures for molecular dynamics tend to produce slightly worse structures.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] Slight improvements have been observed in cases where significant restraints were used during the simulation.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] The two most common and large-scale sources of error in homology modeling are poor template selection and inaccuracies in target-template sequence alignment.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] Alignment errors may be minimized by the use of a multiple alignment even if only one template is used, and by the iterative refinement of local regions of low similarity.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] A lesser source of model errors are errors in the template structure.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] The PDBREPORT Archived 2007-05-31 at the Wayback Machine database lists several million, mostly very small but occasionally dramatic, errors in experimental (template) structures that have been deposited in the PDB.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] Serious local errors can arise in homology models where an insertion or deletion mutation or a gap in a solved structure result in a region of target sequence for which there is no corresponding template.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] This problem can be minimized by the use of multiple templates, but the method is complicated by the templates' differing local structures around the gap and by the likelihood that a missing region in one experimental structure is also missing in other structures of the same protein family.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] Missing regions are most common in loops where high local flexibility increases the difficulty of resolving the region by structure-determination methods.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] Although some guidance is provided even with a single template by the positioning of the ends of the missing region, the longer the gap, the more difficult it is to model.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] Loops of up to about 9 residues can be modeled with moderate accuracy in some cases if the local alignment is correct.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] Larger regions are often modeled individually using ab initio structure prediction techniques, although this approach has met with only isolated success.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] The rotameric states of side chains and their internal packing arrangement also present difficulties in homology modeling, even in targets for which the backbone structure is relatively easy to predict.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] This is partly due to the fact that many side chains in crystal structures are not in their "optimal" rotameric state as a result of energetic factors in the hydrophobic core and in the packing of the individual molecules in a protein crystal.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] One method of addressing this problem requires searching a rotameric library to identify locally low-energy combinations of packing states.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] It has been suggested that a major reason that homology modeling so difficult when target-template sequence identity lies below 30% is that such proteins have broadly similar folds but widely divergent side chain packing arrangements.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] Uses of the structural models include protein–protein interaction prediction, protein–protein docking, molecular docking, and functional annotation of genes identified in an organism's genome.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] Even low-accuracy homology models can be useful for these purposes, because their inaccuracies tend to be located in the loops on the protein surface, which are normally more variable even between closely related proteins.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] The functional regions of the protein, especially its active site, tend to be more highly conserved and thus more accurately modeled.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] Homology models can also be used to identify subtle differences between related proteins that have not all been solved structurally.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] For example, the method was used to identify cation binding sites on the Na+/K+ ATPase and to propose hypotheses about different ATPases' binding affinity.
[src:alphafold-prediction/homology-modeling] Used in conjunction with molecular dynamics simulations, homology models can also generate hypotheses about the kinetics and dynamics of a protein, as in studies of the ion selectivity of a potassium channel.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Protein structure prediction is one of the most important goals pursued by computational biology and addresses Levinthal's paradox.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Accurate structure prediction has important applications in medicine (for example, in drug design) and biotechnology (for example, in novel enzyme design).
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Starting in 1994, the performance of current methods is assessed biennially in the *Critical Assessment of Structure Prediction* (CASP) experiment.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] A continuous evaluation of protein structure prediction web servers is performed by the community project *Continuous Automated Model EvaluatiOn* (CAMEO3D).
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Proteins are chains of amino acids joined together by peptide bonds.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Many conformations of this chain are possible due to the rotation of the main chain about the two torsion angles φ and ψ at the Cα atom.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] This **conformational flexibility** is responsible for differences in the three-dimensional structure of proteins.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] The peptide bonds in the chain are polar, i.e. they have separated positive and negative charges (partial charges) in the carbonyl group, which can act as hydrogen bond acceptor and in the NH group, which can act as hydrogen bond donor.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] These groups can therefore interact in the protein structure.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Proteins consist mostly of 20 different types of L-α-amino acids (the proteinogenic amino acids).
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] These can be classified according to the chemistry of the side chain, which also plays an important structural role.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Glycine takes on a special position, as it has the smallest side chain, only one hydrogen atom, and therefore can increase the local flexibility in the protein structure.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Cysteine in contrast can react with another cysteine residue to form one cystine and thereby form a cross link stabilizing the whole structure.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Protein structure arises from a sequence of secondary structure elements, such as α helices and β sheets.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] In secondary structures, regular patterns of H-bonds are formed between the main chain NH and CO groups of spatially neighboring amino acids, and the amino acids have similar Φ and ψ angles.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Formation of these secondary structures efficiently satisfies the hydrogen bonding capacities of the peptide bonds.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] The secondary structures can be tightly packed in the protein core in a hydrophobic environment, but they can also be present at a polar protein surface.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Each amino acid side chain has a limited volume to occupy and a limited number of possible interactions with other nearby side chains, a situation that must be taken into account in molecular modeling and alignments.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] The α-helix is the most abundant type of secondary structure in proteins.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] The α-helix has 3.6 amino acids per turn with an H-bond formed between every fourth residue; the average length is 10 amino acids (3 turns) or 10 Å but varies from 5 to 40 (1.5 to 11 turns).
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] The alignment of the H-bonds creates a dipole moment for the helix with a resulting partial positive charge at the amino end of the helix.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Because this region has free NH2 groups, it will interact with negatively charged groups such as phosphates.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] The most common location of α-helices is at the surface of protein cores, where they provide an interface with the aqueous environment.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] The inner-facing side of the helix tends to have hydrophobic amino acids and the outer-facing side hydrophilic amino acids.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Thus, every third of four amino acids along the chain will tend to be hydrophobic, a pattern that can be quite readily detected.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] In the leucine zipper motif, a repeating pattern of leucines on the facing sides of two adjacent helices is highly predictive of the motif.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] A helical-wheel plot can be used to show this repeated pattern.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Other α-helices buried in the protein core or in cellular membranes have a higher and more regular distribution of hydrophobic amino acids, and are highly predictive of such structures.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Helices exposed on the surface have a lower proportion of hydrophobic amino acids.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Amino acid content can be predictive of an α-helical region.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Regions richer in alanine (A), glutamic acid (E), leucine (L), and methionine (M) and poorer in proline (P), glycine (G), tyrosine (Y), and serine (S) tend to form an α-helix.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Proline destabilizes or breaks an α-helix but can be present in longer helices, forming a bend.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] β-sheets are formed by H-bonds between an average of 5–10 consecutive amino acids in one portion of the chain with another 5–10 farther down the chain.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] The interacting regions may be adjacent, with a short loop in between, or far apart, with other structures in between.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Every chain may run in the same direction to form a parallel sheet, or in the reverse direction to form an antiparallel sheet, or the chains may form a mixed sheet.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] The pattern of hydrogen bonding is different in the parallel and antiparallel configurations.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Each amino acid in the interior strands of the sheet forms two H-bonds with neighboring amino acids, whereas each amino acid on the outside strands forms only one bond with an interior strand.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Looking across the sheet at right angles to the strands, more distant strands are rotated slightly counterclockwise to form a left-handed twist.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] The Cα-atoms alternate above and below the sheet in a pleated structure, and the R side groups of the amino acids alternate above and below the pleats.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] The Φ and Ψ angles of the amino acids in sheets vary considerably in one region of the Ramachandran plot.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] It is more difficult to predict the location of β-sheets than of α-helices.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] The situation improves somewhat when the amino acid variation in multiple sequence alignments is taken into account.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Parts of the protein may have fixed three-dimensional structure without regular structures.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] They should not be confused with disordered or unfolded segments of proteins or random coil, an unfolded polypeptide chain lacking any fixed three-dimensional structure.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] These parts are frequently called "deltas" (*Δ*) because they connect β-sheets and α-helices.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Deltas are usually located at protein surface, and therefore mutations of their residues are more easily tolerated.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Having more substitutions, insertions, and deletions in a certain region of a sequence alignment maybe an indication of some delta.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] The positions of introns in genomic DNA may correlate with the locations of loops in the encoded protein .
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Deltas also tend to have charged and polar amino acids and are frequently a component of active sites.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Proteins may be classified according to both structural and sequential similarity.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] For structural classification, the sizes and spatial arrangements of secondary structures described in the above paragraph are compared in known three-dimensional structures.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Classification based on sequence similarity was historically the first to be used.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Initially, similarity based on alignments of whole sequences was performed.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Later, proteins were classified on the basis of the occurrence of conserved amino acid patterns.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Databases that classify proteins by one or more of these schemes are available.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] In considering protein classification schemes, it is important to keep several observations in mind.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] First, two entirely different protein sequences from different evolutionary origins may fold into a similar structure.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Conversely, the sequence of an ancient gene for a given structure may have diverged considerably in different species while at the same time maintaining the same basic structural features.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Recognizing any remaining sequence similarity in such cases may be a very difficult task.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Second, two proteins that share a significant degree of sequence similarity either with each other or with a third sequence also share an evolutionary origin and should share some structural features also.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] However, gene duplication and genetic rearrangements during evolution may give rise to new gene copies, which can then evolve into proteins with new function and structure.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] The more commonly used terms for evolutionary and structural relationships among proteins are listed below.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Many additional terms are used for various kinds of structural features found in proteins.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Descriptions of such terms may be found at the CATH Web site, the Structural Classification of Proteins (SCOP) Web site, and a Glaxo Wellcome tutorial on the Swiss bioinformatics Expasy Web site.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] a localized combination of amino acid side groups within the tertiary (three-dimensional) or quaternary (protein subunit) structure that can interact with a chemically specific substrate and that provides the protein with biological activity.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Proteins of very different amino acid sequences may fold into a structure that produces the same active site.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] is the relative orientations of secondary structures in a three-dimensional structure without regard to whether or not they share a similar loop structure.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] a type of architecture that also has a conserved loop structure.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] is a conserved amino acid sequence pattern in a family of proteins.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] The pattern includes a series of possible matches at each position in the represented sequences, but there are not any inserted or deleted positions in the pattern or in the sequences.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] By way of contrast, sequence profiles are a type of scoring matrix that represents a similar set of patterns that includes insertions and deletions.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] a term used to classify protein domains according to their secondary structural content and organization.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] were originally recognized by Levitt and Chothia (1976), and several others have been added in the SCOP database.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Three classes are given in the CATH database: mainly-α, mainly-β, and α–β, with the α–β class including both alternating α/β and α+β structures.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] the portion of a folded protein molecule that comprises the hydrophobic interior of α-helices and β-sheets.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] The compact structure brings together side groups of amino acids into close enough proximity so that they can interact.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] When comparing protein structures, as in the SCOP database, core is the region common to most of the structures that share a common fold or that are in the same superfamily.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] In structure prediction, core is sometimes defined as the arrangement of secondary structures that is likely to be conserved during evolutionary change.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] a segment of a polypeptide chain that can fold into a three-dimensional structure irrespective of the presence of other segments of the chain.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] The separate domains of a given protein may interact extensively or may be joined only by a length of polypeptide chain.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] A protein with several domains may use these domains for functional interactions with different molecules.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] a group of proteins of similar biochemical function that are more than 50% identical when aligned.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] A protein family comprises proteins with the same function in different organisms (orthologous sequences) but may also include proteins in the same organism (paralogous sequences) derived from gene duplication and rearrangements.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] If a multiple sequence alignment of a protein family reveals a common level of similarity throughout the lengths of the proteins, PIR refers to the family as a homeomorphic family.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] The aligned region is referred to as a homeomorphic domain, and this region may comprise several smaller homology domains that are shared with other families.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Families may be further subdivided into subfamilies or grouped into superfamilies based on respective higher or lower levels of sequence similarity.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] The SCOP database reports 1296 families and the CATH database (version 1.7 beta), reports 1846 families.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] When the sequences of proteins with the same function are examined in greater detail, some are found to share high sequence similarity.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] They are obviously members of the same family by the above criteria.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] However, others are found that have very little, or even insignificant, sequence similarity with other family members.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] In such cases, the family relationship between two distant family members A and C can often be demonstrated by finding an additional family member B that shares significant similarity with both A and C.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Thus, B provides a connecting link between A and C.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Another approach is to examine distant alignments for highly conserved matches.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] At a level of identity of 50%, proteins are likely to have the same three-dimensional structure, and the identical atoms in the sequence alignment will also superimpose within approximately 1 Å in the structural model.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Thus, if the structure of one member of a family is known, a reliable prediction may be made for a second member of the family, and the higher the identity level, the more reliable the prediction.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Protein structural modeling can be performed by examining how well the amino acid substitutions fit into the core of the three-dimensional structure.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] ) and the DALI/FSSP Web site, two structures that have a significant level of structural similarity but not necessarily significant sequence similarity.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] similar to structural motif, includes a larger combination of secondary structural units in the same configuration.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Thus, proteins sharing the same fold have the same combination of secondary structures that are connected by similar loops.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] An example is the Rossman fold comprising several alternating α helices and parallel β strands.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] In the SCOP, CATH, and FSSP databases, the known protein structures have been classified into hierarchical levels of structural complexity with the fold as a basic level of classification.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] an extended sequence pattern, generally found by sequence alignment methods, that indicates a common evolutionary origin among the aligned sequences.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] A homology domain is generally longer than motifs.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] The domain may include all of a given protein sequence or only a portion of the sequence.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Some domains are complex and made up of several smaller homology domains that became joined to form a larger one during evolution.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] a region of conserved amino acid patterns comprising one or more motifs and considered to be a fundamental unit of structure or function.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] The presence of a module has also been used to classify proteins into families.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] a conserved pattern of amino acids that is found in two or more proteins.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] catalog, a motif is an amino acid pattern that is found in a group of proteins that have a similar biochemical activity, and that often is near the active site of the protein.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Examples of sequence motif databases are the Prosite catalog and the Stanford Motifs Database.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] a combination of several secondary structural elements produced by the folding of adjacent sections of the polypeptide chain into a specific three-dimensional configuration.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] An example is the helix-loop-helix motif.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Structural motifs are also referred to as supersecondary structures and folds.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] represents a conserved region in a multiple sequence alignment with no gaps.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Each matrix column represents the variation found in one column of the multiple sequence alignment.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] represents the amino acid variation found in an alignment of proteins that fall into the same structural class.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Matrix columns represent the amino acid variation found at one amino acid position in the aligned structures.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] the linear amino acid sequence of a protein, which chemically is a polypeptide chain composed of amino acids joined by peptide bonds.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] a scoring matrix that represents a multiple sequence alignment of a protein family.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] The profile is usually obtained from a well-conserved region in a multiple sequence alignment.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] The profile is in the form of a matrix with each column representing a position in the alignment and each row one of the amino acids.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Matrix values give the likelihood of each amino acid at the corresponding position in the alignment.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] The profile is moved along the target sequence to locate the best scoring regions by a dynamic programming algorithm.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Gaps are allowed during matching and a gap penalty is included in this case as a negative score when no amino acid is matched.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] a scoring matrix that represents which amino acids should fit well and which should fit poorly at sequential positions in a known protein structure.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Profile columns represent sequential positions in the structure, and profile rows represent the 20 amino acids.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] As with a sequence profile, the structural profile is moved along a target sequence to find the highest possible alignment score by a dynamic programming algorithm.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Gaps may be included and receive a penalty.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] The resulting score provides an indication as to whether or not the target protein might adopt such a structure.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] the three-dimensional configuration of a protein molecule comprising several independent polypeptide chains.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] the interactions that occur between the C, O, and NH groups on amino acids in a polypeptide chain to form α-helices, β-sheets, turns, loops, and other forms, and that facilitate the folding into a three-dimensional structure.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] a group of protein families of the same or different lengths that are related by distant yet detectable sequence similarity.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Originally, Dayhoff defined the cutoff for superfamily status as being the chance that the sequences are not related of 10 6, on the basis of an alignment score (Dayhoff et al.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Proteins with few identities in an alignment of the sequences but with a convincingly common number of structural and functional features are placed in the same superfamily.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] At the level of three-dimensional structure, superfamily proteins will share common structural features such as a common fold, but there may also be differences in the number and arrangement of secondary structures.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] to refer to superfamilies that are composed of sequences that can be aligned from end to end, representing a sharing of single sequence homology domain, a region of similarity that extends throughout the alignment.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] This domain may also comprise smaller homology domains that are shared with other protein families and superfamilies.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Although a given protein sequence may contain domains found in several superfamilies, thus indicating a complex evolutionary history, sequences will be assigned to only one homeomorphic superfamily based on the presence of similarity throughout a multiple sequence alignment.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] The superfamily alignment may also include regions that do not align either within or at the ends of the alignment.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] In contrast, sequences in the same family align well throughout the alignment.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] a term with similar meaning to a structural motif.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Tertiary structure is the three-dimensional or globular structure formed by the packing together or folding of secondary structures of a polypeptide chain.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] The accuracy of current protein secondary structure prediction methods is assessed in weekly benchmarks such as LiveBench and EVA.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Early methods of secondary structure prediction, introduced in the 1960s and early 1970s, focused on identifying likely alpha helices and were based mainly on helix-coil transition models.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Significantly more accurate predictions that included beta sheets were introduced in the 1970s and relied on statistical assessments based on probability parameters derived from known solved structures.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] These methods, applied to a single sequence, are typically at most about 60–65% accurate, and often underpredict beta sheets.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Since the 1980s, artificial neural networks have been applied to the prediction of protein structures.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] The evolutionary conservation of secondary structures can be exploited by simultaneously assessing many homologous sequences in a multiple sequence alignment, by calculating the net secondary structure propensity of an aligned column of amino acids.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] In concert with larger databases of known protein structures and modern machine learning methods such as neural nets and support vector machines, these methods can achieve up to 80% overall accuracy in globular proteins.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] The theoretical upper limit of accuracy is around 90%, partly due to idiosyncrasies in DSSP assignment near the ends of secondary structures, where local conformations vary under native conditions but may be forced to assume a single conformation in crystals due to packing constraints.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Dramatic conformational changes related to the protein's function or environment can also alter local secondary structure.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] To date, over 20 different secondary structure prediction methods have been developed.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] One of the first algorithms was Chou–Fasman method, which relies predominantly on probability parameters determined from relative frequencies of each amino acid's appearance in each type of secondary structure.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] The original Chou-Fasman parameters, determined from the small sample of structures solved in the mid-1970s, produce poor results compared to modern methods, though the parameterization has been updated since it was first published.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] The Chou-Fasman method is roughly 50–60% accurate in predicting secondary structures.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] The next notable program was the GOR method is an information theory-based method.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] It uses the more powerful probabilistic technique of Bayesian inference.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] The approach is both more sensitive and more accurate than that of Chou and Fasman because amino acid structural propensities are only strong for a small number of amino acids such as proline and glycine.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Weak contributions from each of many neighbors can add up to strong effects overall.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] The original GOR method was roughly 65% accurate and is dramatically more successful in predicting alpha helices than beta sheets, which it frequently mispredicted as loops or disorganized regions.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Another big step forward was using machine learning methods.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] First artificial neural networks methods were used.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] As a training sets they use solved structures to identify common sequence motifs associated with particular arrangements of secondary structures.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] PSIPRED and JPRED are some of the most known programs based on neural networks for protein secondary structure prediction.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Next, support vector machines have proven particularly useful for predicting the locations of turns, which are difficult to identify with statistical methods.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Extensions of machine learning techniques attempt to predict more fine-grained local properties of proteins, such as backbone dihedral angles in unassigned regions.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Both SVMs and neural networks have been applied to this problem.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] More recently, real-value torsion angles can be accurately predicted by SPINE-X and successfully employed for ab initio structure prediction.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] It is reported that in addition to the protein sequence, secondary structure formation depends on other factors.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] For example, it is reported that secondary structure tendencies depend also on local environment, solvent accessibility of residues, protein structural class, and even the organism from which the proteins are obtained.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Based on such observations, some studies have shown that secondary structure prediction can be improved by addition of information about protein structural class, residue accessible surface area and also contact number information.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] The practical role of protein structure prediction is now more important than ever.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Massive amounts of protein sequence data are produced by modern large-scale DNA sequencing efforts such as the Human Genome Project.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Despite community-wide efforts in structural genomics, the output of experimentally determined protein structures—typically by time-consuming and relatively expensive X-ray crystallography or NMR spectroscopy—is lagging far behind the output of protein sequences.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] The protein structure prediction remains an extremely difficult and unresolved undertaking.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] The two main problems are the calculation of protein free energy and finding the global minimum of this energy.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] A protein structure prediction method must explore the space of possible protein structures which is astronomically large.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] These problems can be partially bypassed in "comparative" or homology modeling and fold recognition methods, in which the search space is pruned by the assumption that the protein in question adopts a structure that is close to the experimentally determined structure of another homologous protein.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] In contrast, the de novo protein structure prediction methods must explicitly resolve these problems.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] The progress and challenges in protein structure prediction have been reviewed by Zhang.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Most tertiary structure modelling methods, such as Rosetta, are optimized for modelling the tertiary structure of single protein domains.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] A step called **domain parsing**, or **domain boundary prediction**, is usually done first to split a protein into potential structural domains.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] As with the rest of tertiary structure prediction, this can be done comparatively from known structures or *ab initio* with the sequence only (usually by machine learning, assisted by covariation).
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] The structures for individual domains are docked together in a process called **domain assembly** to form the final tertiary structure.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] As of 2009, a 50-residue protein could be simulated atom-by-atom on a supercomputer for 1 millisecond.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] As of 2012, comparable stable-state sampling could be done on a standard desktop with a new graphics card and more sophisticated algorithms.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] A much larger simulation timescales can be achieved using coarse-grained modeling.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] The assumption is when single residue mutations are slightly deleterious, compensatory mutations may occur to restabilize residue-residue interactions.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] This early work used what are known as *local* methods to calculate correlated mutations from protein sequences, but suffered from indirect false correlations which result from treating each pair of residues as independent of all other pairs.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] In 2011, a different, and this time *global* statistical approach, demonstrated that predicted coevolved residues were sufficient to predict the 3D fold of a protein, providing there are enough sequences available (>1,000 homologous sequences are needed).
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] The method, EVfold, uses no homology modeling, threading or 3D structure fragments and can be run on a standard personal computer even for proteins with hundreds of residues.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] The accuracy of the contacts predicted using this and related approaches has now been demonstrated on many known structures and contact maps, including the prediction of experimentally unsolved transmembrane proteins.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Comparative protein modeling uses previously solved structures as starting points, or templates.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] This is effective because it appears that although the number of actual proteins is vast, there is a limited set of tertiary structural motifs to which most proteins belong.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] It has been suggested that there are only around 2,000 distinct protein folds in nature, though there are many millions of different proteins.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] The comparative protein modeling can combine with the evolutionary covariation in the structure prediction.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Accurate packing of the amino acid side chains represents a separate problem in protein structure prediction.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Methods that specifically address the problem of predicting side-chain geometry include dead-end elimination and the self-consistent mean field methods.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] The side chain conformations with low energy are usually determined on the rigid polypeptide backbone and using a set of discrete side chain conformations known as "rotamers".
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] The methods attempt to identify the set of rotamers that minimize the model's overall energy.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] These methods use rotamer libraries, which are collections of favorable conformations for each residue type in proteins.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Rotamer libraries may contain information about the conformation, its frequency, and the standard deviations about mean dihedral angles, which can be used in sampling.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Rotamer libraries are derived from structural bioinformatics or other statistical analysis of side-chain conformations in known experimental structures of proteins, such as by clustering the observed conformations for tetrahedral carbons near the staggered (60°, 180°, −60°) values.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Rotamer libraries can be backbone-independent, secondary-structure-dependent, or backbone-dependent.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Backbone-independent rotamer libraries make no reference to backbone conformation, and are calculated from all available side chains of a certain type (for instance, the first example of a rotamer library, done by Ponder and Richards at Yale in 1987).
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Secondary-structure-dependent libraries present different dihedral angles and/or rotamer frequencies for $\alpha$ -helix, $\beta$ -sheet, or coil secondary structures.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Backbone-dependent rotamer libraries present conformations and/or frequencies dependent on the local backbone conformation as defined by the backbone dihedral angles $\phi$ and $\psi$ , regardless of secondary structure.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] The modern versions of these libraries as used in most software are presented as multidimensional distributions of probability or frequency, where the peaks correspond to the dihedral-angle conformations considered as individual rotamers in the lists.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Some versions are based on very carefully curated data and are used primarily for structure validation, while others emphasize relative frequencies in much larger data sets and are the form used primarily for structure prediction, such as the Dunbrack rotamer libraries.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] In the case of complexes of two or more proteins, where the structures of the proteins are known or can be predicted with high accuracy, protein–protein docking methods can be used to predict the structure of the complex.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Information of the effect of mutations at specific sites on the affinity of the complex helps to understand the complex structure and to guide docking methods.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] A great number of software tools for protein structure prediction exist.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Approaches include homology modeling, protein threading, *ab initio* methods, secondary structure prediction, and transmembrane helix and signal peptide prediction.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] In particular, deep learning based on long short-term memory has been used for this purpose since 2007, when it was successfully applied to protein homology detection and to predict subcellular localization of proteins.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Some recent successful methods based on the CASP experiments include I-TASSER, HHpred and AlphaFold.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] In 2021, AlphaFold was reported to perform best.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Knowing the structure of a protein often allows functional prediction as well.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] For instance, collagen is folded into a long-extended fiber-like chain and it makes it a fibrous protein.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Recently, several techniques have been developed to predict protein folding and thus protein structure, for example, Itasser, and AlphaFold.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] AlphaFold was one of the first AIs to predict protein structures.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] It was introduced by Google's DeepMind in the 13th CASP competition, which was held in 2018.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] AlphaFold relies on a neural network approach, which directly predicts the 3D coordinates of all non-hydrogen atoms for a given protein using the amino acid sequence and aligned homologous sequences.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] The AlphaFold network consists of a trunk which processes the inputs through repeated layers, and a structure module which introduces an explicit 3D structure.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Earlier neural networks for protein structure prediction used LSTM.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Since AlphaFold outputs protein coordinates directly, AlphaFold produces predictions in graphics processing unit (GPU) minutes to GPU hours, depending on the length of protein sequence.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] The European Bioinformatics Institute together with DeepMind have constructed the AlphaFold – EBI database for predicted protein structures.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] AlphaFold2, was introduced in CASP14, and is capable of predicting protein structures to near experimental accuracy.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] AlphaFold was swiftly followed by RoseTTAFold and later by OmegaFold and the ESM Metagenomic Atlas.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] 2022 demonstrated the application of protein structure prediction in genome annotation, specifically in identifying functional protein isoforms using computationally predicted structures, available at https://www.isoform.io.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] This study highlights the promise of protein structure prediction as a genome annotation tool and presents a practical, structure-guided approach that can be used to enhance the annotation of any genome.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] In 2024, David Baker and Demis Hassabis (along with John M.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Jumper) were awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry for their contributions to computational protein modeling, including the development of AlphaFold2, an AI-based model for protein structure prediction.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] AlphaFold2's accuracy has been evaluated against experimentally determined protein structures using metrics such as root-mean-square deviation (RMSD).
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] The median RMSD between different experimental structures of the same protein is approximately 0.6 Å, while the median RMSD between AlphaFold2 predictions and experimental structures is around 1 Å.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] For regions where AlphaFold2 assigns high confidence, the median RMSD is about 0.6 Å, comparable to the variability observed between different experimental structures.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] However, in low-confidence regions, the RMSD can exceed 2 Å, indicating greater deviations.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] In proteins with multiple domains connected by flexible linkers, AlphaFold2 predicts individual domain structures accurately but may assign random relative positions to these domains.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] Additionally, AlphaFold2 does not account for structural constraints such as the membrane plane, sometimes placing protein domains in positions that would physically clash with the membrane.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] CASP, which stands for Critical Assessment of Techniques for Protein Structure Prediction, is a community-wide experiment for protein structure prediction taking place every two years since 1994.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] CASP provides with an opportunity to assess the quality of available human, non-automated methodology (human category) and automatic servers for protein structure prediction (server category, introduced in the CASP7).
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] The CAMEO3D Continuous Automated Model EvaluatiOn Server evaluates automated protein structure prediction servers on a weekly basis using blind predictions for newly release protein structures.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-structure-prediction] CAMEO publishes the results on its website.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-tertiary-structure] The science of the tertiary structure of proteins has progressed from one of hypothesis to one of detailed definition.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-tertiary-structure] Although Emil Fischer had suggested proteins were made of polypeptide chains and amino acid side chains, it was Dorothy Maud Wrinch who incorporated geometry into the prediction of protein structures.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-tertiary-structure] Wrinch demonstrated this with the *Cyclol* model, the first prediction of the structure of a globular protein.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-tertiary-structure] Under favorable conditions, such as confident knowledge of secondary structure, contemporary methods are sometimes able to predict the tertiary structure of small proteins (<120 residues) *de novo* to within 5 Å (0.5 nm).
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-tertiary-structure] A protein folded into its native state or native conformation typically has a lower Gibbs free energy (a combination of enthalpy and entropy) than the unfolded conformation.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-tertiary-structure] A protein will tend towards low-energy conformations, which will determine the protein's fold in the cellular environment.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-tertiary-structure] Because many similar conformations will have similar energies, protein structures are dynamic, fluctuating between these similar structures.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-tertiary-structure] Globular proteins have a core of hydrophobic amino acid residues and a surface region of water-exposed, charged, hydrophilic residues.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-tertiary-structure] This arrangement may stabilize interactions within the tertiary structure.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-tertiary-structure] For example, in secreted proteins, which are not bathed in cytoplasm, disulfide bonds between cysteine residues help to maintain the tertiary structure.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-tertiary-structure] There is a commonality of stable tertiary structures seen in proteins of diverse function and diverse evolution.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-tertiary-structure] For example, the TIM barrel, named for the enzyme triosephosphateisomerase, is a common tertiary structure as is the highly stable, dimeric, coiled coil structure.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-tertiary-structure] Hence, proteins may be classified by the structures they hold.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-tertiary-structure] Databases of proteins which use such a classification include *SCOP* and *CATH*.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-tertiary-structure] Folding kinetics may trap a protein in a high-energy conformation, i.e. a high-energy intermediate conformation blocks access to the lowest-energy conformation.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-tertiary-structure] The high-energy conformation may contribute to the function of the protein.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-tertiary-structure] For example, the influenza hemagglutinin protein is a single polypeptide chain which when activated, is proteolytically cleaved to form two polypeptide chains.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-tertiary-structure] The two chains are held in a high-energy conformation.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-tertiary-structure] When the local pH drops, the protein undergoes an energetically favorable conformational rearrangement that enables it to penetrate the host cell membrane.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-tertiary-structure] Some tertiary protein structures may exist in long-lived states that are not the expected most stable state.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-tertiary-structure] For example, many serpins (serine protease inhibitors) show this metastability.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-tertiary-structure] They undergo a conformational change when a loop of the protein is cut by a protease.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-tertiary-structure] It is commonly assumed that the native state of a protein is also the most thermodynamically stable and that a protein will reach its native state, given its chemical kinetics, before it is translated.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-tertiary-structure] Protein chaperones within the cytoplasm of a cell assist a newly synthesised polypeptide to attain its native state.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-tertiary-structure] Prediction of protein tertiary structure relies on knowing the protein's primary structure and comparing the possible predicted tertiary structure with known tertiary structures in protein data banks.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-tertiary-structure] This only takes into account the cytoplasmic environment present at the time of protein synthesis to the extent that a similar cytoplasmic environment may also have influenced the structure of the proteins recorded in the protein data bank.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-tertiary-structure] The structure of a protein, such as an enzyme, may change upon binding of its natural ligands, for example a cofactor.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-tertiary-structure] In this case, the structure of the protein bound to the ligand is known as holo structure, while the unbound protein has an apo structure.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-tertiary-structure] The knowledge of the tertiary structure of soluble globular proteins is more advanced than that of membrane proteins because the former are easier to study with available technology.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-tertiary-structure] X-ray crystallography is the most common tool used to determine protein structure.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-tertiary-structure] It provides high resolution of the structure but it does not give information about protein's conformational flexibility.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-tertiary-structure] Protein NMR gives comparatively lower resolution of protein structure.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-tertiary-structure] However, it can provide information about conformational changes of a protein in solution.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-tertiary-structure] Cryogenic electron microscopy (cryo-EM) can give information about both a protein's tertiary and quaternary structure.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-tertiary-structure] It is particularly well-suited to large proteins and symmetrical complexes of protein subunits.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-tertiary-structure] Dual polarisation interferometry provides complementary information about surface captured proteins.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-tertiary-structure] It assists in determining structure and conformation changes over time.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-tertiary-structure] The Folding@home project at the University of Pennsylvania is a distributed computing research effort which uses approximately 5 petaFLOPS (≈10 x86 petaFLOPS) of available computing.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-tertiary-structure] It aims to find an algorithm which will consistently predict protein tertiary and quaternary structures given the protein's amino acid sequence and its cellular conditions.
[src:alphafold-prediction/protein-tertiary-structure] A list of software for protein tertiary structure prediction can be found at List of protein structure prediction software.
[src:alphafold-prediction/threading-protein-sequence] In molecular biology, **protein threading**, also known as **fold recognition**, is a method of protein modeling which is used to model those proteins which have the same fold as proteins of known structures, but do not have homologous proteins with known structure.
[src:alphafold-prediction/threading-protein-sequence] It differs from the homology modeling method of structure prediction as it (protein threading) is used for proteins which do not have their homologous protein structures deposited in the Protein Data Bank (PDB), whereas homology modeling is used for those proteins which do.
[src:alphafold-prediction/threading-protein-sequence] Threading works by using statistical knowledge of the relationship between the structures deposited in the PDB and the sequence of the protein which one wishes to model.
[src:alphafold-prediction/threading-protein-sequence] The prediction is made by "threading" (i.e. placing, aligning) each amino acid in the target sequence to a position in the template structure, and evaluating how well the target fits the template.
[src:alphafold-prediction/threading-protein-sequence] After the best-fit template is selected, the structural model of the sequence is built based on the alignment with the chosen template.
[src:alphafold-prediction/threading-protein-sequence] Protein threading is based on two basic observations: that the number of different folds in nature is fairly small (approximately 1300); and that 90% of the new structures submitted to the PDB in the past three years have similar structural folds to ones already in the PDB.
[src:alphafold-prediction/threading-protein-sequence] The Structural Classification of Proteins database (SCOP) provides a detailed and comprehensive description of the structural and evolutionary relationships of known structure.
[src:alphafold-prediction/threading-protein-sequence] Proteins are classified to reflect both structural and evolutionary relatedness.
[src:alphafold-prediction/threading-protein-sequence] The design of the scoring function: Design a good scoring function to measure the fitness between target sequences and templates based on the knowledge of the known relationships between the structures and the sequences.
[src:alphafold-prediction/threading-protein-sequence] A good scoring function should contain mutation potential, environment fitness potential, pairwise potential, secondary structure compatibilities, and gap penalties.
[src:alphafold-prediction/threading-protein-sequence] The quality of the energy function is closely related to the prediction accuracy, especially the alignment accuracy.
[src:alphafold-prediction/threading-protein-sequence] Threading alignment: Align the target sequence with each of the structure templates by optimizing the designed scoring function.
[src:alphafold-prediction/threading-protein-sequence] This step is one of the major tasks of all threading-based structure prediction programs that take into account the pairwise contact potential; otherwise, a dynamic programming algorithm can fulfill it.
[src:alphafold-prediction/threading-protein-sequence] Threading prediction: Select the threading alignment that is statistically most probable as the threading prediction.
[src:alphafold-prediction/threading-protein-sequence] Then construct a structure model for the target by placing the backbone atoms of the target sequence at their aligned backbone positions of the selected structural template.
[src:alphafold-prediction/threading-protein-sequence] Homology modeling and protein threading are both template-based methods and there is no rigorous boundary between them in terms of prediction techniques.
[src:alphafold-prediction/threading-protein-sequence] But the protein structures of their targets are different.
[src:alphafold-prediction/threading-protein-sequence] Homology modeling is for those targets which have homologous proteins with known structure (usually/maybe of same family), while protein threading is for those targets with only fold-level homology found.
[src:alphafold-prediction/threading-protein-sequence] In other words, homology modeling is for "easier" targets and protein threading is for "harder" targets.
[src:alphafold-prediction/threading-protein-sequence] Homology modeling treats the template in an alignment as a sequence, and only sequence homology is used for prediction.
[src:alphafold-prediction/threading-protein-sequence] Protein threading treats the template in an alignment as a structure, and both sequence and structure information extracted from the alignment are used for prediction.
[src:alphafold-prediction/threading-protein-sequence] When there is no significant homology found, protein threading can make a prediction based on the structure information.
[src:alphafold-prediction/threading-protein-sequence] That also explains why protein threading may be more effective than homology modeling in many cases.
[src:alphafold-prediction/threading-protein-sequence] In practice, when the sequence identity in a sequence sequence alignment is low (i.e. <25%), homology modeling may not produce a significant prediction.
[src:alphafold-prediction/threading-protein-sequence] In this case, if there is distant homology found for the target, protein threading can generate a good prediction.
[src:alphafold-prediction/threading-protein-sequence] Fold recognition methods can be broadly divided into two types: those that derive a 1-D profile for each structure in the fold library and align the target sequence to these profiles; and those that consider the full 3-D structure of the protein template.
[src:alphafold-prediction/threading-protein-sequence] A simple example of a profile representation would be to take each amino acid in the structure and simply label it according to whether it is buried in the core of the protein or exposed on the surface.
[src:alphafold-prediction/threading-protein-sequence] More elaborate profiles might take into account the local secondary structure (e.g. whether the amino acid is part of an alpha helix) or even evolutionary information (how conserved the amino acid is).
[src:alphafold-prediction/threading-protein-sequence] In the 3-D representation, the structure is modeled as a set of inter-atomic distances, i.e. the distances are calculated between some or all of the atom pairs in the structure.
[src:alphafold-prediction/threading-protein-sequence] This is a much richer and far more flexible description of the structure, but is much harder to use in calculating an alignment.
[src:alphafold-prediction/threading-protein-sequence] The profile-based fold recognition approach was first described by Bowie, Lüthy and David Eisenberg in 1991.
[src:alphafold-prediction/threading-protein-sequence] The term *threading* was first coined by David Jones, William R.
[src:alphafold-prediction/threading-protein-sequence] Taylor and Janet Thornton in 1992, and originally referred specifically to the use of a full 3-D structure atomic representation of the protein template in fold recognition.
[src:alphafold-prediction/threading-protein-sequence] Today, the terms threading and fold recognition are frequently (though somewhat incorrectly) used interchangeably.
[src:alphafold-prediction/threading-protein-sequence] Fold recognition methods are widely used and effective because it is believed that there are a strictly limited number of different protein folds in nature, mostly as a result of evolution but also due to constraints imposed by the basic physics and chemistry of polypeptide chains.
[src:alphafold-prediction/threading-protein-sequence] There is, therefore, a good chance (currently 70-80%) that a protein which has a similar fold to the target protein has already been studied by X-ray crystallography or nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) spectroscopy and can be found in the PDB.
[src:alphafold-prediction/threading-protein-sequence] Currently there are nearly 1300 different protein folds known, but new folds are still being discovered every year due in significant part to the ongoing structural genomics projects.
[src:alphafold-prediction/threading-protein-sequence] Many different algorithms have been proposed for finding the correct threading of a sequence onto a structure, though many make use of dynamic programming in some form.
[src:alphafold-prediction/threading-protein-sequence] For full 3-D threading, the problem of identifying the best alignment is very difficult (it is an NP-hard problem for some models of threading).
[src:alphafold-prediction/threading-protein-sequence] Researchers have made use of many combinatorial optimization methods such as conditional random fields, simulated annealing, branch and bound, and linear programming, searching to arrive at heuristic solutions.
[src:alphafold-prediction/threading-protein-sequence] It is interesting to compare threading methods to methods which attempt to align two protein structures (protein structural alignment), and indeed many of the same algorithms have been applied to both problems.
